[src:integral-transforms/convolution-theorem] In mathematics, the **convolution theorem** states that under suitable conditions the Fourier transform of a convolution of two functions (or signals) is the product of their Fourier transforms.
[src:integral-transforms/convolution-theorem] More generally, convolution in one domain (e.g., time domain) equals point-wise multiplication in the other domain (e.g., frequency domain).
[src:integral-transforms/convolution-theorem] Other versions of the convolution theorem are applicable to various Fourier-related transforms.
[src:integral-transforms/convolution-theorem] where ${\mathcal {F}}$ denotes the **Fourier transform operator**.
[src:integral-transforms/convolution-theorem] The transform may be normalized in other ways, in which case constant scaling factors (typically $2\pi$ or ${\sqrt {2\pi }}$ ) will appear in the convolution theorem below.
[src:integral-transforms/convolution-theorem] In this context the asterisk denotes convolution, instead of standard multiplication.
[src:integral-transforms/convolution-theorem] The tensor product symbol $\otimes$ is sometimes used instead.
[src:integral-transforms/convolution-theorem] The theorem also generally applies to multi-dimensional functions.
[src:integral-transforms/convolution-theorem] This theorem also holds for the Laplace transform, the two-sided Laplace transform and, when suitably modified, for the Mellin transform and Hartley transform (see Mellin inversion theorem).
[src:integral-transforms/convolution-theorem] It can be extended to the Fourier transform of abstract harmonic analysis defined over locally compact abelian groups.
[src:integral-transforms/convolution-theorem] In practice the non-zero portion of components u and v are often limited to duration $P,$ but nothing in the theorem requires that.
[src:integral-transforms/convolution-theorem] where ${\mathcal {F}}$ denotes the **Fourier series integral**.
[src:integral-transforms/convolution-theorem] By a derivation similar to Eq.1, there is an analogous theorem for sequences, such as samples of two continuous functions, where now ${\mathcal {F}}$ denotes the **discrete-time Fourier transform** (DTFT) operator.
[src:integral-transforms/convolution-theorem] $U(f)$ and $V(f),$ as defined above, are periodic, with a period of 1.
[src:integral-transforms/convolution-theorem] These functions occur as the result of sampling U and V at intervals of $1/N$ and performing an inverse **discrete Fourier transform** (DFT) on N samples (see § Sampling the DTFT).
[src:integral-transforms/convolution-theorem] is also N -periodic, and is called a **periodic convolution**.
[src:integral-transforms/convolution-theorem] Under the right conditions, it is possible for this N -length sequence to contain a distortion-free segment of a $u*v$ convolution.
[src:integral-transforms/convolution-theorem] But when the non-zero portion of the $u(n)$ or $v(n)$ sequence is equal or longer than $N,$ some distortion is inevitable.
[src:integral-transforms/convolution-theorem] Such is the case when the $V(k/N)$ sequence is obtained by directly sampling the DTFT of the infinitely long § Discrete Hilbert transform impulse response.
[src:integral-transforms/convolution-theorem] This form is often used to efficiently implement numerical convolution by computer.
[src:integral-transforms/convolution-theorem] As a partial reciprocal, it has been shown that any linear transform that turns convolution into a product is the DFT (up to a permutation of coefficients).
[src:integral-transforms/convolution-theorem] Here, " $\cdot$ " represents the Hadamard product, and " * " represents a convolution between the two matrices.
[src:integral-transforms/convolution-theorem] The convolution theorem extends to tempered distributions.
[src:integral-transforms/convolution-theorem] But $\alpha =F\{u\}$ must be "rapidly decreasing" towards $-\infty$ and $+\infty$ in order to guarantee the existence of both, convolution and multiplication product.
[src:integral-transforms/convolution-theorem] Equivalently, if $u=F^{-1}\{\alpha \}$ is a smooth "slowly growing" ordinary function, it guarantees the existence of both, multiplication and convolution product.
[src:integral-transforms/convolution-theorem] In particular, every compactly supported tempered distribution, such as the Dirac delta, is "rapidly decreasing".
[src:integral-transforms/convolution-theorem] Equivalently, bandlimited functions, such as the function that is constantly 1 are smooth "slowly growing" ordinary functions.
[src:integral-transforms/convolution-theorem] If, for example, $v\equiv \operatorname {\text{Ш}}$ is the Dirac comb both equations yield the Poisson summation formula and if, furthermore, $u\equiv \delta$ is the Dirac delta then $\alpha \equiv 1$ is constantly one and these equations yield the Dirac comb identity.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] In mathematics, the **Fourier transform** (**FT**) is an integral transform that takes a function as input and outputs another function that describes the extent to which various frequencies are present in the original function.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] The output of the transform is a complex valued function of frequency.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] The term *Fourier transform* refers to both the mathematical operation and to this complex-valued function.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] When a distinction needs to be made, the output of the operation is sometimes called the frequency domain representation of the original function.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] The Fourier transform is analogous to decomposing the sound of a musical chord into the intensities of its constituent pitches.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] Functions that are localized in the time domain have Fourier transforms that are spread out across the frequency domain and vice versa, a phenomenon known as the uncertainty principle.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] The critical case for this principle is the Gaussian function, of substantial importance in probability theory and statistics as well as in the study of physical phenomena exhibiting normal distribution (e.g., diffusion).
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] The Fourier transform of a Gaussian function is another Gaussian function.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] Joseph Fourier introduced sine and cosine transforms (which correspond to the imaginary and real components of the modern Fourier transform) in his study of heat transfer, where Gaussian functions appear as solutions of the heat equation.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] The Fourier transform can be formally defined as an improper Riemann integral, making it an integral transform, although this definition is not suitable for many applications requiring a more sophisticated integration theory.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] For example, many relatively simple applications use the Dirac delta function, which can be treated formally as if it were a function, but the justification requires a mathematically more sophisticated viewpoint.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] The Fourier transform can also be generalized to functions of several variables on Euclidean space, sending a function of 3-dimensional "position space" to a function of 3-dimensional momentum (or a function of space and time to a function of 4-momentum).
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] This idea makes the spatial Fourier transform very natural in the study of waves, as well as in quantum mechanics, where it is important to be able to represent wave solutions as functions of either position or momentum and sometimes both.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] In general, functions to which Fourier methods are applicable are complex-valued, and possibly vector-valued.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] The latter is routinely employed to handle periodic functions.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] The fast Fourier transform (FFT) is an algorithm for computing the DFT.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] When $f(x)$ is (Lebesgue) integrable over the whole real line, the above integral converges for all $\xi \in \mathbb {R}$ , and ${\widehat {f}}(\xi )$ is a uniformly continuous function of $\xi$ which decays to zero as ⁠ $\xi \to \infty$ ⁠.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] However, the Fourier transform can also be defined for (generalized) functions for which the Lebesgue integral **Eq.1** does not make sense.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] Interpreting the integral suitably (e.g. as an improper integral for locally integrable functions) extends the Fourier transform to functions that are not necessarily integrable over the whole real line.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] More generally, the Fourier transform also applies to generalized functions like the Dirac delta (and all other tempered distributions), in which case it is defined by duality rather than an integral.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] The functions f and ${\widehat {f}}$ are referred to as a **Fourier transform pair**.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] When the independent variable (⁠ x ⁠) represents *time* (often denoted by ⁠ t ⁠), the transform variable (⁠ $\xi$ ⁠) represents frequency (often denoted by ⁠ f ⁠).
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] For example, if time has the unit second, then frequency has the unit hertz.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] The transform variable can also be written in terms of angular frequency, ⁠ $\omega =2\pi \xi$ ⁠, with the unit radian per second.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] Furthermore, ${\widehat {f}}\in L^{\infty }\cap C_{0}(\mathbb {R} )$ is bounded, uniformly continuous and (by the Riemann–Lebesgue lemma) vanishing at infinity.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] Here $C_{0}(\mathbb {R} )$ denotes the space of continuous functions on $\mathbb {R}$ that approach 0 as x approaches positive or negative infinity.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] The space $L^{1}(\mathbb {R} )$ is the space of measurable functions for which the norm $\|f\|_{1}$ is finite, modulo the equivalence relation of equality almost everywhere.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] The Fourier transform on $L^{1}(\mathbb {R} )$ is one-to-one.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] However, there is no easy characterization of the image, and thus no easy characterization of the inverse transform.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] In particular, **Eq.2** is no longer valid, as it was stated only under the hypothesis that $f(x)$ was "sufficiently nice" (e.g., $f(x)$ decays with all derivatives).
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] While **Eq.1** defines the Fourier transform for (complex-valued) functions in ⁠ $L^{1}(\mathbb {R} )$ ⁠, it is not well-defined for other integrability classes, most importantly the space of square-integrable functions ⁠ $L^{2}(\mathbb {R} )$ ⁠.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] However, the Fourier transform on the dense subspace $L^{1}\cap L^{2}(\mathbb {R} )\subset L^{2}(\mathbb {R} )$ admits a unique continuous extension to a unitary operator on ⁠ $L^{2}(\mathbb {R} )$ ⁠.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] This extension is important in part because, unlike the case of ⁠ $L^{1}$ ⁠, the Fourier transform is an automorphism of the space ⁠ $L^{2}(\mathbb {R} )$ ⁠.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] In such cases, the Fourier transform can be obtained explicitly by regularizing the integral, and then passing to a limit.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] In practice, the integral is often regarded as an improper integral instead of a proper Lebesgue integral, but sometimes for convergence one needs to use weak limit or principal value instead of the (pointwise) limits implicit in an improper integral.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] Titchmarsh (1986) and Dym & McKean (1985) each gives three rigorous ways of extending the Fourier transform to square integrable functions using this procedure.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] A general principle in working with the $L^{2}$ Fourier transform is that finite linear combinations of Gaussians are dense in ⁠ $L^{1}\cap L^{2}$ ⁠, and the various features of the Fourier transform, such as its unitarity, are easily inferred for Gaussians.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] A feature of the $L^{1}$ Fourier transform is that it is a homomorphism of Banach algebras from $L^{1}$ equipped with the convolution operation to the Banach algebra of continuous functions under the $L^{\infty }$ (supremum) norm.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] The conventions chosen in this article are those of harmonic analysis, such that the Fourier transform is both unitary on ⁠ $L^{2}$ ⁠ and an algebra homomorphism from ⁠ ${1}$ ⁠ to ⁠ $L^{\infty }$ ⁠, without renormalizing the Lebesgue measure.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] In 1822, Fourier claimed (see *Joseph Fourier § The Analytic Theory of Heat*) that any function, whether continuous or discontinuous, can be expanded into a series of sines.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] That important work was corrected and expanded upon by others to provide the foundation for the various forms of the Fourier transform used since.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] Likewise, the intuitive interpretation of **Eq.1** is that multiplying $f(x)$ by $e^{-i2\pi \xi x}$ has the effect of subtracting $\xi$ from every frequency component of function ⁠ $f(x)$ ⁠.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] Only the component that was at frequency $\xi$ can produce a non-zero value of the infinite integral, because (at least formally) all the other shifted components are oscillatory and integrate to zero (see *§ Example*).
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] It is noteworthy how easily the product was simplified using the polar form, and how easily the rectangular form was deduced by an application of Euler's formula.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] Euler's formula introduces the possibility of negative ⁠ $\xi$ ⁠.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] Only certain complex-valued $f(x)$ have transforms ⁠ ${\widehat {f}}=0,\ \forall \ \xi <0$ ⁠.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] (See *Analytic signal*; a simple example is ⁠ $e^{i2\pi \xi _{0}x}\ (\xi _{0}>0)$ ⁠.) But negative frequency is necessary to characterize all other complex-valued ⁠ $f(x)$ ⁠, found in signal processing, partial differential equations, radar, nonlinear optics, quantum mechanics, and others.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] But it cannot determine the actual sign of ⁠ $\xi _{0}$ ⁠, because $\cos(2\pi \xi _{0}x)$ and $\cos(2\pi (-\xi _{0})x)$ are indistinguishable on just the real numbers line.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] The Fourier transform of a periodic function cannot be defined using the integral formula directly.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] In order for integral in **Eq.1** to be defined the function must be absolutely integrable.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] Instead it is common to use Fourier series.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] It is possible to extend the definition to include periodic functions by viewing them as tempered distributions.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] This makes it possible to see a connection between the Fourier series and the Fourier transform for periodic functions that have a convergent Fourier series.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] In other words, the Fourier transform is a Dirac comb function whose *teeth* are multiplied by the Fourier series coefficients.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] The Fourier transform of an integrable function f can be sampled at regular intervals of arbitrary length ⁠ $1/P$ ⁠.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] The integrability of f ensures the periodic summation converges.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] When $f(x)$ has compact support, $f_{P}(x)$ has a finite number of terms within the interval of integration.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] When $f(x)$ does not have compact support, numerical evaluation of $f_{P}(x)$ requires an approximation, such as tapering $f(x)$ or truncating the number of terms.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] The frequency variable must have inverse units to the units of the original function's domain (typically named t or ⁠ x ⁠).
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] For example, if t is measured in seconds, $\xi$ should be in cycles per second or hertz.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] If the scale of time is in units of $2\pi$ seconds, then another Greek letter $\omega$ is typically used instead to represent angular frequency (where ⁠ $\omega =2\pi \xi$ ⁠) in units of radians per second.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] If using x for units of length, then $\xi$ must be in inverse length, e.g., wavenumbers.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] That is to say, there are two versions of the real line: one that is the range of t and measured in units of ⁠ t ⁠, and the other that is the range of $\xi$ and measured in inverse units to the units of ⁠ t ⁠.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] These two distinct versions of the real line cannot be equated with each other.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] Therefore, the Fourier transform goes from one space of functions to a different space of functions: functions that have a different domain of definition.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] In general, $\xi$ must always be taken to be a linear form on the space of its domain, which is to say that the second real line is the dual space of the first real line.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] (See the article *Linear algebra* for a more formal explanation and for more details.) This point of view becomes essential in generalizations of the Fourier transform to general symmetry groups, including the case of Fourier series.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] The various definitions resulting from different choices of units differ by various constants.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] In other conventions, the Fourier transform has i in the exponent instead of −*i*, and vice versa for the inversion formula.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] This convention is common in modern physics and is the default for Wolfram Alpha, and does not mean that the frequency has become negative, since there is no canonical definition of positivity for frequency of a complex wave.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] Many of the identities involving the Fourier transform remain valid in those conventions, provided all terms that explicitly involve *i* have it replaced by −*i*.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] In electrical engineering the letter *j* is typically used for the imaginary unit instead of *i* because *i* is used for current.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] When using dimensionless units, the constant factors might not be written in the transform definition.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] In probability theory and mathematical statistics, the use of the Fourier—Stieltjes transform is preferred, because many random variables are not of continuous type, and do not possess a density function, and one must treat not functions but distributions, i.e., measures that possess "atoms".
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] From the higher point of view of group characters, which is much more abstract, all these arbitrary choices disappear, as will be explained in the later section of this article, which treats the notion of the Fourier transform of a function on a locally compact abelian group.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] Let $f(x)$ and $h(x)$ represent *integrable functions* Lebesgue-measurable on the real line satisfying: $\int _{-\infty }^{\infty }|f(x)|\,dx<\infty .$ We denote the Fourier transforms of these functions as ${\widehat {f}}(\xi )$ and ${\widehat {h}}(\xi )$ respectively.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] When the real and imaginary parts of a complex function are decomposed into their even and odd parts, there are four components, denoted below by the subscripts RE, RO, IE, and IO.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] In particular, if f is *real*, then ${\widehat {f}}$ is conjugate symmetric (a.k.a.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] The integral of f over its domain is the total mass or DC bias of the function.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] The Fourier transform may be defined in some cases for non-integrable functions, but the Fourier transforms of integrable functions have several strong properties.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] However, ${\widehat {f}}$ need not be integrable.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] For example, the Fourier transform of the rectangular function, which is integrable, is the sinc function, which is not Lebesgue integrable, because its improper integrals behave analogously to the alternating harmonic series, in converging to a sum without being absolutely convergent.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] It is not generally possible to write the *inverse transform* as a Lebesgue integral.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] However, when both f and ${\widehat {f}}$ are integrable, the inverse equality $f(x)=\int _{-\infty }^{\infty }{\widehat {f}}(\xi )e^{i2\pi x\xi }\,d\xi$ holds for almost every x.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] As a result, the Fourier transform is injective on *L*1(**R**).
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] Let ⁠ $f(x)$ ⁠ and ⁠ $g(x)$ ⁠ be integrable, and let ⁠ ${\widehat {f}}$ ⁠ and ⁠ ${\widehat {g}}$ ⁠ be their Fourier transforms.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] Plancherel's theorem makes it possible to extend the Fourier transform, by a continuity argument, to a unitary operator on ⁠ $L^{2}(\mathbb {R} )$ ⁠.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] Plancherel's theorem has the interpretation in the sciences that the Fourier transform preserves the energy of the original quantity.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] The terminology of these formulas is not quite standardised.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] Parseval's theorem was proved only for Fourier series, and was first proved by Lyapunov.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] But Parseval's formula makes sense for the Fourier transform as well, and so even though in the context of the Fourier transform it was proved by Plancherel, it is still often referred to as Parseval's formula, or Parseval's relation, or even Parseval's theorem.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] See *Pontryagin duality* for a general formulation of this concept in the context of locally compact abelian groups.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] The Fourier transform translates between convolution and multiplication of functions.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] In linear time invariant (LTI) system theory, it is common to interpret ⁠ $g(x)$ ⁠ as the impulse response of an LTI system with input ⁠ $f(x)$ ⁠ and output ⁠ $h(x)$ ⁠, since substituting the unit impulse for ⁠ $f(x)$ ⁠ yields ⁠ $h(x)=g(x)$ ⁠.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] In this case, ⁠ ${\widehat {g}}(\xi )$ ⁠ represents the frequency response of the system.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] Conversely, if ⁠ $f(x)$ ⁠ can be decomposed as the product of two square integrable functions ⁠ $p(x)$ ⁠ and ⁠ $q(x)$ ⁠, then the Fourier transform of ⁠ $f(x)$ ⁠ is given by the convolution of the respective Fourier transforms ⁠ ${\widehat {p}}(\xi )$ ⁠ and ⁠ ${\widehat {q}}(\xi )$ ⁠.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] Suppose *f*(*x*) is differentiable almost everywhere, and both ⁠ f ⁠ and its derivative ⁠ $f'$ ⁠ are integrable (in ⁠ $L^{1}(\mathbb {R} )$ ⁠).
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] By applying the Fourier transform and using these formulas, some ordinary differential equations can be transformed into algebraic equations, which are much easier to solve.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] These formulas also give rise to the rule of thumb "⁠ $f(x)$ ⁠ is smooth if and only if ⁠ ${\widehat {f}}(\xi )$ ⁠ quickly falls to ⁠ 0 ⁠ for ⁠ $\vert \xi \vert \to \infty$ ⁠".
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] The Fourier transform is a linear transform that has eigenfunctions obeying ⁠ ${\mathcal {F}}[\psi ]=\lambda \psi$ ⁠, with ⁠ $\lambda \in \mathbb {C}$ ⁠.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] In other words, every solution $\psi (x)$ and its Fourier transform ${\widehat {\psi }}(\xi )$ obey the same equation.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] Assuming uniqueness of the solutions, every solution $\psi (x)$ must therefore be an eigenfunction of the Fourier transform.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] The simplest allowable $U(x)=x$ leads to the standard normal distribution.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] The simplest example is provided by ⁠ $W(x)=x^{2}$ ⁠, which is equivalent to considering the Schrödinger equation for the quantum harmonic oscillator.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] The corresponding solutions provide an important choice of an orthonormal basis for *L*2(**R**) and are given by the "physicist's" Hermite functions.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] In other words, the Hermite functions form a complete orthonormal system of eigenfunctions for the Fourier transform on ⁠ $L^{2}(\mathbb {R} )$ ⁠.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] However, this choice of eigenfunctions is not unique.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] Because of ${\mathcal {F}}^{4}=\mathrm {id}$ there are only four different eigenvalues of the Fourier transform (the fourth roots of unity ⁠ $\pm 1$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\pm i$ ⁠) and any linear combination of eigenfunctions with the same eigenvalue gives another eigenfunction.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] As a consequence of this, it is possible to decompose *L*2(**R**) as a direct sum of four spaces *H*0, *H*1, *H*2, and *H*3 where the Fourier transform acts on H*k* simply by multiplication by *i**k*.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] This approach to define the Fourier transform was first proposed by Norbert Wiener.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] Among other properties, Hermite functions decrease exponentially fast in both frequency and time domains, and they are thus used to define a generalization of the Fourier transform, namely the fractional Fourier transform used in time–frequency analysis.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] In physics, this transform was introduced by Edward Condon.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] This change of basis becomes possible because the Fourier transform is a unitary transform when using the right conventions.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] It can be interpreted as the generator of fractional Fourier transforms for arbitrary values of t, and of the conventional continuous Fourier transform ${\mathcal {F}}$ for the particular value ⁠ $t=\pi /2$ ⁠, with the Mehler kernel implementing the corresponding active transform.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] The eigenfunctions of N are the Hermite functions ⁠ $\psi _{n}(x)$ ⁠, which are therefore also eigenfunctions of ⁠ ${\mathcal {F}}$ ⁠.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] Upon extending the Fourier transform to distributions the Dirac comb is also an eigenfunction of the Fourier transform.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] Under suitable conditions on the function ⁠ f ⁠, it can be recovered from its Fourier transform ⁠ ${\widehat {f}}$ ⁠.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] In particular the Fourier transform is invertible (under suitable conditions).
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] These are not true for all functions, but are true under various conditions, which are the content of the various forms of the Fourier inversion theorem.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] This fourfold periodicity of the Fourier transform is similar to a rotation of the plane by 90°, particularly as the two-fold iteration yields a reversal, and in fact this analogy can be made precise.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] This can be further generalized to linear canonical transformations, which can be visualized as the action of the special linear group SL2(**R**) on the time–frequency plane, with the preserved symplectic form corresponding to the uncertainty principle, below.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] This approach is particularly studied in signal processing, under time–frequency analysis.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] The Heisenberg group is a certain group of unitary operators on the Hilbert space *L*2(**R**) of square integrable complex valued functions f on the real line, generated by the translations (*Ty f*)(*x*) = *f* (*x* + *y*) and multiplication by *e**i*2π*ξx*, (*Mξ f*)(*x*) = *e**i*2π*ξx* *f* (*x*).
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] These operators do not commute, as their (group) commutator is $\left(M_{\xi }^{-1}T_{y}^{-1}M_{\xi }T_{y}f\right)(x)=e^{i2\pi \xi y}f(x),$ which is multiplication by the constant (independent of x) *e**i*2π*ξy* ∈ *U*(1) (the circle group of unit modulus complex numbers).
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] The above procedure describes not only the group structure, but also a standard unitary representation of *H*1 on a Hilbert space, which we denote by *ρ* : *H*1 → *B*(*L*2(**R**)).
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] Define the linear automorphism of **R**2 by $J{\begin{pmatrix}x\\\xi \end{pmatrix}}={\begin{pmatrix}-\xi \\x\end{pmatrix}}$ so that *J*2 = −*I*.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] According to the Stone–von Neumann theorem, the unitary representations ρ and *ρ* ∘ *j* are unitarily equivalent, so there is a unique intertwiner *W* ∈ *U*(*L*2(**R**)) such that $\rho \circ j=W\rho W^{*}.$ This operator W is the Fourier transform.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] Many of the standard properties of the Fourier transform are immediate consequences of this more general framework.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p01] For example, the square of the Fourier transform, *W*2, is an intertwiner associated with *J*2 = −*I*, and so we have (*W*2*f*)(*x*) = *f* (−*x*) is the reflection of the original function f.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] The integral for the Fourier transform ${\widehat {f}}(\xi )=\int _{-\infty }^{\infty }e^{-2i\pi t\xi }f(t)\,dt$ can be studied for complex values of its argument ξ.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] Depending on the properties of f, this might not converge off the real axis at all, or it might converge to a complex analytic function for all values of *ξ* = *σ* + *iτ*, or something in between.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] (In this case, f is supported on [−*a*, *a*].) This can be expressed by saying that *f̂* is an entire function that is rapidly decreasing in σ (for fixed τ) and of exponential growth in τ (uniformly in σ).
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] (If f is not smooth, but only *L*2, a corresponding version holds with the rapid-decrease condition replaced by the appropriate *L*2 condition.) The space of such functions of a complex variable is called the Paley–Wiener space.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] This theorem has been generalised to semisimple Lie groups.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] If f is supported on the half-line *t* ≥ 0, then f is said to be "causal" because the impulse response function of a physically realisable filter must have this property, as no effect can precede its cause.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] Paley and Wiener showed that then, under suitable integrability hypotheses, *f̂* extends to a holomorphic function on the complex lower half-plane *τ* < 0 that tends to zero as τ goes to −∞.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] A simple converse in this form is false; precise converses require additional growth or Hardy-space hypotheses.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] The Fourier transform *f̂*(*ξ*) is related to the Laplace transform *F*(*s*), which is also used for the solution of differential equations and the analysis of filters.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] It may happen that a function f for which the Fourier integral does not converge on the real axis at all nevertheless has a complex Fourier transform defined in some region of the complex plane.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] If f is causal and the integrals converge, then ⁠ ${\widehat {f}}(i\tau )=F(-2\pi \tau )$ ⁠.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] Thus, extending the Fourier transform to the complex domain means it includes the Laplace transform as a special case in the case of causal functions—but with the change of variable *s* = *i*2π*ξ*.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] From another, perhaps more classical viewpoint, the Laplace transform by its form involves an additional exponential regulating term that lets it converge outside of the imaginary line where the Fourier transform is defined.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] As such it can converge for functions and integrals with at most exponential growth in the regulated direction, whereas the original Fourier decomposition cannot, enabling analysis of systems with divergent or critical elements.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] Two particular examples from linear signal processing are the construction of allpass filter networks from critical comb and mitigating filters via exact pole-zero cancellation on the unit circle.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] Such designs are common in audio processing, where highly nonlinear phase response is sought for, as in reverb.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] Furthermore, when extended pulselike impulse responses are sought for signal processing work, the easiest way to produce them is to have one circuit that produces a divergent time response, and then to cancel its divergence through a delayed opposite and compensatory response.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] There, only the delay circuit in-between admits a classical Fourier description, which is critical.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] Both the circuits to the side are unstable, and do not admit a convergent Fourier decomposition.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] However, they do admit a Laplace domain description, with compatible half-planes of convergence in the complex plane (or in the discrete case, the Z-plane), wherein their effects cancel.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] In modern mathematics the Laplace transform is conventionally subsumed under the aegis of Fourier methods.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] Both of them are subsumed by the far more general, and more abstract, idea of harmonic analysis.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] Therefore, the Fourier inversion formula can use integration along different lines, parallel to the real axis.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] This theorem implies the Mellin inversion formula for the Laplace transformation, $f(t)={\frac {1}{i2\pi }}\int _{b-i\infty }^{b+i\infty }F(s)e^{st}\,ds$ for any *b* > *a*, where *F*(*s*) is the Laplace transform of *f*(*t*).
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] The hypotheses can be weakened, as in standard Fourier inversion results, to *f*(*t*) *e*−*at* being *L*1, provided that f be of bounded variation in a closed neighborhood of t (cf.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] Dini test), the value of f at t be taken to be the arithmetic mean of the left and right limits, and that the integrals be taken in the sense of Cauchy principal values.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] The Fourier transform can be defined in any arbitrary number of dimensions n.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] As with the one-dimensional case, there are many conventions.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] Alternatively, **ξ** can be viewed as belonging to the dual vector space ⁠ $\mathbb {R} ^{n\star }$ ⁠, in which case the dot product becomes the contraction of **x** and **ξ**, usually written as ⟨**x**, **ξ**⟩.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] All of the basic properties listed above hold for the n-dimensional Fourier transform, as do Plancherel's and Parseval's theorem.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] When the function is integrable, the Fourier transform is still uniformly continuous and the Riemann–Lebesgue lemma holds.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] Generally speaking, the more concentrated *f*(*x*) is, the more spread out its Fourier transform *f̂*(*ξ*) must be.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] In particular, the scaling property of the Fourier transform may be seen as saying: if we squeeze a function in x, its Fourier transform stretches out in ξ.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] It is not possible to arbitrarily concentrate both a function and its Fourier transform.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] Suppose *f*(*x*) is an integrable and square-integrable function.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] It follows from the Plancherel theorem that *f̂*(*ξ*) is also normalized.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] In probability terms, this is the second moment of |*f*(*x*)|2 about zero.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] In other words, where f is a (normalized) Gaussian function with variance *σ*2/2π, centered at zero, and its Fourier transform is a Gaussian function with variance *σ*−2/2π.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] Gaussian functions are examples of Schwartz functions (see the discussion on tempered distributions below).
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] With this constant properly taken into account, the inequality above becomes the statement of the Heisenberg uncertainty principle.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] The equality is attained for a Gaussian, as in the previous case.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] Fourier's original formulation of the transform did not use complex numbers, but rather sines and cosines.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] Statisticians and others still use this form.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] This is called an expansion as a trigonometric integral, or a Fourier integral expansion.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] Older literature refers to the two transform functions, the Fourier cosine transform, a, and the Fourier sine transform, b.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] The function f can be recovered from the sine and cosine transform using $f(t)=2\int _{0}^{\infty }\int _{-\infty }^{\infty }f(\tau )\cos {\bigl (}2\pi \lambda (\tau -t){\bigr )}\,d\tau \,d\lambda .$ together with trigonometric identities.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] This is referred to as Fourier's integral formula.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] Let the set of homogeneous harmonic polynomials of degree k on **R***n* be denoted by **A***k*.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] The set **A***k* consists of the solid spherical harmonics of degree k.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] The solid spherical harmonics play a similar role in higher dimensions to the Hermite polynomials in dimension one.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] The space *L*2(**R***n*) is then a direct sum of the spaces **H***k* and the Fourier transform maps each space **H***k* to itself and it is possible to characterize the action of the Fourier transform on each space **H***k*.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] Here *J*(*n* + 2*k* − 2)/2 denotes the Bessel function of the first kind with order ⁠*n* + 2*k* − 2/2⁠.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] When *k* = 0 this gives a useful formula for the Fourier transform of a radial function.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] This is essentially the Hankel transform.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] Moreover, there is a simple recursion relating the cases *n* + 2 and n allowing to compute, e.g., the three-dimensional Fourier transform of a radial function from the one-dimensional one.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] In higher dimensions it becomes interesting to study *restriction problems* for the Fourier transform.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] The Fourier transform of an integrable function is continuous and the restriction of this function to any set is defined.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] But for a square-integrable function the Fourier transform could be a general *class* of square integrable functions.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] As such, the restriction of the Fourier transform of an *L*2(**R***n*) function cannot be defined on sets of measure 0.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] It is still an active area of study to understand restriction problems in *L**p* for 1 < *p* < 2.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] It is possible in some cases to define the restriction of a Fourier transform to a set S, provided S has non-zero curvature.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] The case when S is the unit sphere in **R***n* is of particular interest.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] In this case the Tomas–Stein restriction theorem states that the restriction of the Fourier transform to the unit sphere in **R***n* is a bounded operator on *L**p* provided 1 ≤ *p* ≤ ⁠2*n* + 2/*n* + 3⁠.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] One notable difference between the Fourier transform in 1 dimension versus higher dimensions concerns the partial sum operator.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] Consider an increasing collection of measurable sets *E**R* indexed by *R* ∈ (0, ∞): such as balls of radius R centered at the origin, or cubes of side 2*R*.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] For *n* = 1 and 1 < *p* < ∞, if one takes *ER* = (−*R*, *R*), then fR converges to f in *L**p* as R tends to infinity, by the boundedness of the Hilbert transform.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] Naively one may hope the same holds true for *n* > 1.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] In the case that ER is taken to be a cube with side length R, then convergence still holds.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] Another natural candidate is the Euclidean ball *E**R* = {*ξ* : |*ξ*| < *R*}.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] In order for this partial sum operator to converge, it is necessary that the multiplier for the unit ball be bounded in *L**p*(**R***n*).
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] For *n* ≥ 2 it is a celebrated theorem of Charles Fefferman that the multiplier for the unit ball is never bounded unless *p* = 2.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] In fact, when *p* ≠ 2, this shows that not only may fR fail to converge to f in *L**p*, but for some functions *f* ∈ *L**p*(**R***n*), fR is not even an element of *L**p*.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] The definition of the Fourier transform naturally extends from $L^{1}(\mathbb {R} )$ to ⁠ $L^{1}(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ ⁠.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] The Riemann–Lebesgue lemma shows that if $f\in L^{1}(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ then its Fourier transform actually belongs to the space of continuous functions that vanish at infinity, i.e., ⁠ ${\widehat {f}}\in C_{0}(\mathbb {R} ^{n})\subset L^{\infty }(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ ⁠.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] Similarly to the case of one variable, the Fourier transform can be defined on ⁠ $L^{2}(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ ⁠.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] The Fourier transform in $L^{2}(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ is no longer given by an ordinary Lebesgue integral, although it can be computed by an improper integral, i.e., ${\widehat {f}}(\xi )=\lim _{R\to \infty }\int _{|x|\leq R}f(x)e^{-i2\pi \xi \cdot x}\,dx$ where the limit is taken in the *L*2 sense.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] For an operator to be unitary it is sufficient to show that it is bijective and preserves the inner product.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] The Fourier inversion theorem implies that the transform is bijective.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] So the transform preserves the inner product.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] For ⁠ $1<p<2$ ⁠, the Fourier transform can be defined on $L^{p}(\mathbb {R} )$ by Riesz–Thorin interpolation, which amounts to decomposing such functions into a fat tail part $|f|\leq 1$ in *L*2 plus a fat body part $|f|>1$ in *L*1.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] In each of these spaces, the Fourier transform of a function in *L**p*(**R***n*) is in *L**q*(**R***n*), where *q* = ⁠*p*/*p* − 1⁠ is the Hölder conjugate of p (by the Hausdorff–Young inequality).
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] However, except for *p* = 2, the image is not easily characterized.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] Further extensions become more technical.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] The Fourier transform of functions in *L**p* for the range 2 < *p* < ∞ requires the study of distributions.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] In fact, it can be shown that there are functions in *L**p* with *p* > 2 so that the Fourier transform is not defined as a function.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] One might consider enlarging the domain of the Fourier transform from $L^{1}+L^{2}$ by considering generalized functions, or distributions.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] A distribution on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ is a continuous linear functional on the space $C_{c}^{\infty }(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ of compactly supported smooth functions (i.e. bump functions), equipped with a suitable topology.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] Since $C_{c}^{\infty }(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ is dense in ⁠ $L^{2}(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ ⁠, the Plancherel theorem allows one to extend the definition of the Fourier transform to general functions in $L^{2}(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ by continuity arguments.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] The strategy is then to consider the action of the Fourier transform on $C_{c}^{\infty }(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ and pass to distributions by duality.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] The obstruction to doing this is that the Fourier transform does not map $C_{c}^{\infty }(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ to ⁠ $C_{c}^{\infty }(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ ⁠.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] In fact the Fourier transform of an element in $C_{c}^{\infty }(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ can not vanish on an open set; see the above discussion on the uncertainty principle.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] The Fourier transform can also be defined for tempered distributions ⁠ ${\mathcal {S}}'(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ ⁠, dual to the space of Schwartz functions ⁠ ${\mathcal {S}}(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ ⁠.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] The tempered distributions include well-behaved functions of polynomial growth, distributions of compact support as well as all the integrable functions mentioned above.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] For the definition of the Fourier transform of a tempered distribution, let f and g be integrable functions, and let ${\widehat {f}}$ and ${\widehat {g}}$ be their Fourier transforms respectively.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] Distributions can be differentiated and the above-mentioned compatibility of the Fourier transform with differentiation and convolution remains true for tempered distributions.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] If $\mu$ is the probability distribution of a random variable X then its Fourier–Stieltjes transform is, by definition, a characteristic function.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] If, in addition, the probability distribution has a probability density function, this definition is subject to the usual Fourier transform.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] Stated more generally, when $\mu$ is absolutely continuous with respect to the Lebesgue measure, i.e., $d\mu =f(x)\,dx,$ then ${\widehat {\mu }}(\xi )={\widehat {f}}(\xi ),$ and the Fourier-Stieltjes transform reduces to the usual definition of the Fourier transform.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] That is, the notable difference with the Fourier transform of integrable functions is that the Fourier-Stieltjes transform need not vanish at infinity, i.e., the Riemann–Lebesgue lemma fails for measures.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] Bochner's theorem characterizes which functions may arise as the Fourier–Stieltjes transform of a positive measure on the circle.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] One example of a finite Borel measure that is not a function is the Dirac measure.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] Its Fourier transform is a constant function (whose value depends on the form of the Fourier transform used).
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] The Fourier transform may be generalized to any locally compact abelian group, i.e., an abelian group that is also a locally compact Hausdorff space such that the group operation is continuous.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] If G is a locally compact abelian group, it has a translation invariant measure μ, called Haar measure.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] For a locally compact abelian group G, the set of irreducible, i.e. one-dimensional, unitary representations are called its characters.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] The Riemann–Lebesgue lemma holds in this case; *f̂*(*ξ*) is a function vanishing at infinity on Ĝ.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] The Fourier transform on T = R/Z is an example; here T is a locally compact abelian group, and the Haar measure μ on T can be thought of as the Lebesgue measure on [0,1).
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] Consider a representation of T on the complex plane C thought of as a 1-dimensional complex vector space.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] There is a group of such representations (which are irreducible since C is 1-dim) $\{e_{k}:T\rightarrow GL_{1}(C)=C^{*}\mid k\in Z\}$ where $e_{k}(x)=e^{i2\pi kx}$ for ⁠ $x\in T$ ⁠.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] The character of such representation, that is the trace of $e_{k}(x)$ (thought of as a one-by-one matrix) for each $x\in T$ and ⁠ $k\in Z$ ⁠, is $e^{i2\pi kx}$ itself.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] The group T is no longer finite but still compact, and it preserves the orthonormality of the character table.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] The sequence $\{e_{k}\mid k\in Z\}$ is an orthonormal basis of the space of class functions ⁠ $L^{2}(T,d\mu )$ ⁠.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] The Fourier transform is also a special case of the Gelfand transform.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] In this particular context, it is closely related to the Pontryagin duality map defined above.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] Given an abelian locally compact Hausdorff topological group G, as before we consider the space *L*1(*G*), defined using a Haar measure.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] With convolution as multiplication, *L*1(*G*) is an abelian Banach algebra.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] Taking the completion with respect to the largest possible *C**-norm gives its enveloping *C**-algebra, called the group *C**-algebra *C**(*G*) of G.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] Given any abelian *C**-algebra A, the Gelfand transform gives an isomorphism between A and *C*0(*A*^), where *A*^ is the multiplicative linear functionals, i.e. one-dimensional representations, on A with the weak-* topology.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] The Fourier transform can also be defined for functions on a non-abelian group, provided that the group is compact.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] Removing the assumption that the underlying group is abelian, irreducible unitary representations need not always be one-dimensional.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] This means the Fourier transform on a non-abelian group takes values as Hilbert space operators.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] The Fourier transform on compact groups is a major tool in representation theory and non-commutative harmonic analysis.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] Let G be a compact Hausdorff topological group, and let λ be its normalized Haar measure.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] Let Σ denote the collection of all isomorphism classes of finite-dimensional irreducible unitary representations, along with a definite choice of representation *U*(*σ*) on the Hilbert space *Hσ* of finite dimension *dσ* for each *σ* ∈ Σ.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] The involution on *M*(*G*) is given, for absolutely continuous measures, by $f^{*}(g)={\overline {f(g^{-1})}},$ since compact groups are unimodular.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] The Peter–Weyl theorem holds, and a version of the Fourier inversion formula follows: if *f* ∈ *L*2(*G*), then $f(g)=\sum _{\sigma \in \Sigma }d_{\sigma }\operatorname {tr} \left({\widehat {f}}(\sigma )U_{g}^{(\sigma )}\right),$ where the summation is understood as convergent in the *L*2 sense.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] The generalization of the Fourier transform to the noncommutative situation has also in part contributed to the development of noncommutative geometry.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] In this context, a categorical generalization of the Fourier transform to noncommutative groups is Tannaka–Krein duality, which replaces the group of characters with the category of representations.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] However, this is no longer simply a transform of scalar-valued functions into scalar-valued functions.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] This limits the usefulness of the Fourier transform for analyzing signals that are localized in time, notably transients, or any signal of finite extent.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] As alternatives to the Fourier transform, in time–frequency analysis, one uses time–frequency transforms or time–frequency distributions to represent signals in a form that has some time information and some frequency information – by the uncertainty principle, there is a trade-off between these.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] The following figures provide a visual illustration of how the Fourier transform's integral measures whether a frequency is present in a particular function.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] The first image depicts the function ⁠ $f(t)=\cos(2\pi \ 3t)\ e^{-\pi t^{2}}$ ⁠, which is a 3 Hz cosine wave (the first term) shaped by a Gaussian envelope function (the second term) that smoothly turns the wave on and off.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] The next 2 images show the product ⁠ $f(t)e^{-i2\pi 3t}$ ⁠, which must be integrated to calculate the Fourier transform at +3 Hz.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] The real part of the integrand has a non-negative average value, because the alternating signs of $f(t)$ and $\operatorname {Re} (e^{-i2\pi 3t})$ oscillate at the same rate and in phase, whereas $f(t)$ and $\operatorname {Im} (e^{-i2\pi 3t})$ oscillate at the same rate but with orthogonal phase.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] The absolute value of the Fourier transform at +3 Hz is 0.5, which is relatively large.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] When added to the Fourier transform at -3 Hz (which is identical because we started with a real signal), we find that the amplitude of the 3 Hz frequency component is 1.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] However, when you try to measure a frequency that is not present, both the real and imaginary component of the integral vary rapidly between positive and negative values.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] For instance, the red curve is looking for 5 Hz.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] The absolute value of its integral is nearly zero, indicating that almost no 5 Hz component was in the signal.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] The general situation is usually more complicated than this, but heuristically this is how the Fourier transform measures how much of an individual frequency is present in a function ⁠ $f(t)$ ⁠.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p02] To re-enforce an earlier point, the reason for the response at $\xi =-3$ Hz is because $\cos(2\pi 3t)$ and $\cos(2\pi (-3)t)$ are indistinguishable.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] Linear operations performed in one domain (time or frequency) have corresponding operations in the other domain, which are sometimes easier to perform.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] The operation of differentiation in the time domain corresponds to multiplication by the frequency, so some differential equations are easier to analyze in the frequency domain.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] Also, convolution in the time domain corresponds to ordinary multiplication in the frequency domain (see *Convolution theorem*).
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] After performing the desired operations, transformation of the result can be made back to the time domain.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] Harmonic analysis is the systematic study of the relationship between the frequency and time domains, including the kinds of functions or operations that are "simpler" in one or the other, and has deep connections to many areas of modern mathematics.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] Perhaps the most important use of the Fourier transformation is to solve partial differential equations.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] Many of the equations of the mathematical physics of the nineteenth century can be treated this way.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] As usual, the problem is not to find a solution: there are infinitely many.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] For the heat equation, only one boundary condition can be required (usually the first one).
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] But for the wave equation, there are still infinitely many solutions y that satisfy the first boundary condition.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] But when one imposes both conditions, there is only one possible solution.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] It is easier to find the Fourier transform ŷ of the solution than to find the solution directly.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] After ŷ is determined, we can apply the inverse Fourier transformation to find y.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] First, note that any function of the forms $\cos {\bigl (}2\pi \xi (x\pm t){\bigr )}{\text{ or }}\sin {\bigl (}2\pi \xi (x\pm t){\bigr )}$ satisfies the wave equation.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] These are called the elementary solutions.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] This integral may be interpreted as a continuous linear combination of solutions for the linear equation.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] Now this resembles the formula for the Fourier synthesis of a function.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] In fact, this is the real inverse Fourier transform of *a*± and *b*± in the variable x.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] The third step is to examine how to find the specific unknown coefficient functions *a*± and *b*± that will lead to y satisfying the boundary conditions.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] We are interested in the values of these solutions at *t* = 0.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] These are four linear equations for the four unknowns *a*± and *b*±, in terms of the Fourier sine and cosine transforms of the boundary conditions, which are easily solved by elementary algebra, provided that these transforms can be found.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] In summary, we chose a set of elementary solutions, parametrized by ξ, of which the general solution would be a (continuous) linear combination in the form of an integral over the parameter ξ.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] But this integral was in the form of a Fourier integral.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] The next step was to express the boundary conditions in terms of these integrals, and set them equal to the given functions f and g.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] But these expressions also took the form of a Fourier integral because of the properties of the Fourier transform of a derivative.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] The last step was to exploit Fourier inversion by applying the Fourier transformation to both sides, thus obtaining expressions for the coefficient functions *a*± and *b*± in terms of the given boundary conditions f and g.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] From a higher point of view, Fourier's procedure can be reformulated more conceptually.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] Since there are two variables, we will use the Fourier transformation in both x and t rather than operate as Fourier did, who only transformed in the spatial variables.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] Note that ŷ must be considered in the sense of a distribution since *y*(*x*, *t*) is not going to be *L*1: as a wave, it will persist through time and thus is not a transient phenomenon.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] But it will be bounded and so its Fourier transform can be defined as a distribution.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] The operational properties of the Fourier transformation that are relevant to this equation are that it takes differentiation in x to multiplication by *i*2π*ξ* and differentiation with respect to t to multiplication by *i*2π*f* where f is the frequency.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] Then the wave equation becomes an algebraic equation in ŷ: $\xi ^{2}{\widehat {y}}(\xi ,f)=f^{2}{\widehat {y}}(\xi ,f).$ This is equivalent to requiring *ŷ*(*ξ*, *f*) = 0 unless *ξ* = ±*f*.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] Right away, this explains why the choice of elementary solutions we made earlier worked so well: obviously *ŷ* = *δ*(*ξ* ± *f*) will be solutions.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] Applying Fourier inversion to these delta functions, we obtain the elementary solutions we picked earlier.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] But from the higher point of view, one does not pick elementary solutions, but rather considers the space of all distributions that are supported on the (degenerate) conic *ξ*2 − *f*2 = 0.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] Now, as before, applying the one-variable Fourier transformation in the variable x to these functions of x yields two equations in the two unknown distributions *s*± (which can be taken to be ordinary functions if the boundary conditions are *L*1 or *L*2).
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] From a calculational point of view, the drawback of course is that one must first calculate the Fourier transforms of the boundary conditions, then assemble the solution from these, and then calculate an inverse Fourier transform.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] Closed form formulas are rare, except when there is some geometric symmetry that can be exploited, and the numerical calculations are difficult because of the oscillatory nature of the integrals, which makes convergence slow and hard to estimate.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] For practical calculations, other methods are often used.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] The twentieth century has seen application of these methods to all linear partial differential equations with polynomial coefficients as well as an extension to certain classes of nonlinear partial differential equations.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] Specifically, nonlinear evolution equations (i.e. those equations that describe how a particular quantity evolves in time from a specified initial state) that can be associated with linear eigenvalue problems whose eigenvalues are integrals of the nonlinear equations.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] As it may be considered an extension of Fourier analysis to nonlinear problems, the solution method is called the **nonlinear Fourier transform** (or **inverse scattering transform**) method.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] The Fourier transform is also used in nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) and in other kinds of spectroscopy, e.g. infrared (FTIR).
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] In NMR an exponentially shaped free induction decay (FID) signal is acquired in the time domain and Fourier-transformed to a Lorentzian line-shape in the frequency domain.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] The Fourier transform is also used in magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) and mass spectrometry.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] The Fourier transform is useful in quantum mechanics in at least two different ways.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] To begin with, the basic conceptual structure of quantum mechanics postulates the existence of pairs of complementary variables, connected by the Heisenberg uncertainty principle.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] For example, in one dimension, the spatial variable q of, say, a particle, can only be measured by the quantum mechanical "position operator" at the cost of losing information about the momentum p of the particle.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] Therefore, the physical state of the particle can either be described by a function, called "the wave function", of q or by a function of p but not by a function of both variables.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] The variable p is called the conjugate variable to q.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] In classical mechanics, the physical state of a particle (existing in one dimension, for simplicity of exposition) would be given by assigning definite values to both p and q simultaneously.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] Thus, the set of all possible physical states is the two-dimensional real vector space with a p-axis and a q-axis called the phase space.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] In contrast, quantum mechanics chooses a polarisation of this space in the sense that it picks a subspace of one-half the dimension, for example, the q-axis alone, but instead of considering only points, takes the set of all complex-valued "wave functions" on this axis.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] Nevertheless, choosing the p-axis is an equally valid polarisation, yielding a different representation of the set of possible physical states of the particle.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] Physically realisable states are *L*2, and so by the Plancherel theorem, their Fourier transforms are also *L*2.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] Therefore, the Fourier transform can be used to pass from one way of representing the state of the particle, by a wave function of position, to another way of representing the state of the particle: by a wave function of momentum.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] Infinitely many different polarisations are possible, and all are equally valid.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] Being able to transform states from one representation to another by the Fourier transform is not only convenient but also the underlying reason of the Heisenberg uncertainty principle.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] The other use of the Fourier transform in both quantum mechanics and quantum field theory is to solve the applicable wave equation.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] This is the same as the heat equation except for the presence of the imaginary unit i.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] Fourier methods can be used to solve this equation.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] The "elementary solutions", as we referred to them above, are the so-called "stationary states" of the particle, and Fourier's algorithm, as described above, can still be used to solve the boundary value problem of the future evolution of ψ given its values for *t* = 0.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] Neither of these approaches is of much practical use in quantum mechanics.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] Boundary value problems and the time-evolution of the wave function is not of much practical interest: it is the stationary states that are most important.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] In relativistic quantum mechanics, the Schrödinger equation becomes a wave equation as was usual in classical physics, except that complex-valued waves are considered.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] This is, from the mathematical point of view, the same as the wave equation of classical physics solved above (but with a complex-valued wave, which makes no difference in the methods).
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] This is of great use in quantum field theory: each separate Fourier component of a wave can be treated as a separate harmonic oscillator and then quantized, a procedure known as "second quantization".
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] Fourier methods have been adapted to also deal with non-trivial interactions.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] Finally, the number operator of the quantum harmonic oscillator can be interpreted, for example via the Mehler kernel, as the generator of the Fourier transform ⁠ ${\mathcal {F}}$ ⁠.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] The Fourier transform is used for the spectral analysis of time-series.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] The subject of statistical signal processing does not, however, usually apply the Fourier transformation to the signal itself.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] Even if a real signal is indeed transient, it has been found in practice advisable to model a signal by a function (or, alternatively, a stochastic process) that is stationary in the sense that its characteristic properties are constant over all time.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] The Fourier transform of such a function does not exist in the usual sense, and it has been found more useful for the analysis of signals to instead take the Fourier transform of its autocorrelation function.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] This function is a function of the time-lag τ elapsing between the values of f to be correlated.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] For most functions f that occur in practice, R is a bounded even function of the time-lag τ and for typical noisy signals it turns out to be uniformly continuous with a maximum at *τ* = 0.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] The autocorrelation function, more properly called the autocovariance function unless it is normalized in some appropriate fashion, measures the strength of the correlation between the values of f separated by a time lag.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] This is a way of searching for the correlation of f with its own past.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] It is useful even for other statistical tasks besides the analysis of signals.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] For example, if *f*(*t*) represents the temperature at time t, one expects a strong correlation with the temperature at a time lag of 24 hours.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] This Fourier transform is called the power spectral density function of f.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] The power spectrum, as indicated by this density function P, measures the amount of variance contributed to the data by the frequency ξ.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] In electrical signals, the variance is proportional to the average power (energy per unit time), and so the power spectrum describes how much the different frequencies contribute to the average power of the signal.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] This process is called the spectral analysis of time-series and is analogous to the usual analysis of variance of data that is not a time-series (ANOVA).
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] Knowledge of which frequencies are "important" in this sense is crucial for the proper design of filters and for the proper evaluation of measuring apparatuses.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] It can also be useful for the scientific analysis of the phenomena responsible for producing the data.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] The power spectrum of a signal can also be approximately measured directly by measuring the average power that remains in a signal after all the frequencies outside a narrow band have been filtered out.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] Spectral analysis is carried out for visual signals as well.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] The power spectrum ignores all phase relations, which is good enough for many purposes, but for video signals other types of spectral analysis must also be employed, still using the Fourier transform as a tool.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] A disadvantage of the capital letter notation is when expressing a transform such as ${\widehat {f}}\cdot g$ or ⁠ ${\widehat {f}}'$ ⁠, which become the more awkward ${\mathcal {F}}\{f\cdot g\}$ and ⁠ ${\mathcal {F}}\{f'\}$ ⁠.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] Although tildes may be used as in ${\tilde {f}}$ to indicate Fourier transforms, tildes may also be used to indicate a modification of a quantity with a more Lorentz invariant form, such as ⁠ ${\tilde {dk}}={\frac {dk}{(2\pi )^{3}2\omega }}$ ⁠, so care must be taken.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] Similarly, ${\widehat {f}}$ often denotes the Hilbert transform of ⁠ f ⁠.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] Then the inverse transform can be written: $f(x)=\int _{-\infty }^{\infty }A(\xi )\ e^{i{\bigl (}2\pi \xi x+\varphi (\xi ){\bigr )}}\,d\xi ,$ which is a recombination of all the frequency components of *f*(*x*).
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] Each component is a complex sinusoid of the form *e*2π*ixξ* whose amplitude is *A*(*ξ*) and whose initial phase angle (at *x* = 0) is *φ*(*ξ*).
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] The Fourier transform may be thought of as a mapping on function spaces.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] This mapping is here denoted F and F(*f*) is used to denote the Fourier transform of the function f.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] This mapping is linear, which means that F can also be seen as a linear transformation on the function space and implies that the standard notation in linear algebra of applying a linear transformation to a vector (here the function *f*) can be used to write F *f* instead of F(*f*).
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] Since the result of applying the Fourier transform is again a function, we can be interested in the value of this function evaluated at the value ξ for its variable, and this is denoted either as F *f*(*ξ*) or as (F *f*)(*ξ*).
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] Notice that in the former case, it is implicitly understood that F is applied first to f and then the resulting function is evaluated at ξ, not the other way around.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] In mathematics and various applied sciences, it is often necessary to distinguish between a function f and the value of f when its variable equals x, denoted *f*(*x*).
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] This means that a notation like F(*f*(*x*)) formally can be interpreted as the Fourier transform of the values of f at x.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] Despite this flaw, the previous notation appears frequently, often when a particular function or a function of a particular variable is to be transformed.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] Notice, that the last example is only correct under the assumption that the transformed function is a function of x, not of *x*0.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] As discussed above, the characteristic function of a random variable is the same as the Fourier–Stieltjes transform of its distribution measure, but in this context it is typical to take a different convention for the constants.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] As in the case of the "non-unitary angular frequency" convention above, the factor of 2π appears in neither the normalizing constant nor the exponent.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] Unlike any of the conventions appearing above, this convention takes the opposite sign in the exponent.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] The appropriate computation method largely depends how the original mathematical function is represented and the desired form of the output function.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] In this section we consider both functions of a continuous variable, ⁠ $f(x)$ ⁠, and functions of a discrete variable (i.e. ordered pairs of x and f values).
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] For discrete-valued ⁠ x ⁠, the transform integral becomes a summation of sinusoids, which is still a continuous function of frequency (⁠ $\xi$ ⁠ or ⁠ $\omega$ ⁠).
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] When the sinusoids are harmonically related (i.e. when the x -values are spaced at integer multiples of an interval), the transform is called discrete-time Fourier transform (DTFT).
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] Sampling the DTFT at equally-spaced values of frequency is the most common modern method of computation.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] Efficient procedures, depending on the frequency resolution needed, are described at Discrete-time Fourier transform § Sampling the DTFT.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] The discrete Fourier transform (DFT), used there, is usually computed by a fast Fourier transform (FFT) algorithm.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] When mathematically possible, this provides a transform for a continuum of frequency values.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] Discrete sampling of the Fourier transform can also be done by numerical integration of the definition at each value of frequency for which transform is desired.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] The numerical integration approach works on a much broader class of functions than the analytic approach.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] If the input function is a series of ordered pairs, numerical integration reduces to just a summation over the set of data pairs.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p03] The DTFT is a common subcase of this more general situation.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p04] The following tables record some closed-form Fourier transforms.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p04] For functions *f*(*x*) and *g*(*x*) denote their Fourier transforms by *f̂* and *ĝ*.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p04] Only the three most common conventions are included.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p04] It may be useful to notice that entry 105 gives a relationship between the Fourier transform of a function and the original function, which can be seen as relating the Fourier transform and its inverse.
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p04] The Fourier transforms in this table may be found in Erdélyi (1954) or Kammler (2000, appendix).
[src:integral-transforms/fourier-transform-p04] The Fourier transforms in this table may be found in Campbell & Foster (1948), Erdélyi (1954), or Kammler (2000, appendix).
[src:integral-transforms/hartley-transform] In mathematics, the **Hartley transform** (**HT**) is an integral transform closely related to the Fourier transform (FT), but which transforms real-valued functions to real-valued functions.
[src:integral-transforms/hartley-transform] It was proposed as an alternative to the Fourier transform by Ralph V.
[src:integral-transforms/hartley-transform] Hartley in 1942, and is one of many known Fourier-related transforms.
[src:integral-transforms/hartley-transform] Compared to the Fourier transform, the Hartley transform has the advantages of transforming real functions to real functions (as opposed to requiring complex numbers) and of being its own inverse.
[src:integral-transforms/hartley-transform] The discrete version of the transform, the discrete Hartley transform (DHT), was introduced by Ronald N.
[src:integral-transforms/hartley-transform] The two-dimensional Hartley transform can be computed by an analog optical process similar to an optical Fourier transform (OFT), with the proposed advantage that only its amplitude and sign need to be determined rather than its complex phase.
[src:integral-transforms/hartley-transform] However, optical Hartley transforms do not seem to have seen widespread use.
[src:integral-transforms/hartley-transform] is the cosine-and-sine (cas) or *Hartley* kernel.
[src:integral-transforms/hartley-transform] In engineering terms, this transform takes a signal (function) from the time-domain to the Hartley spectral domain (frequency domain).
[src:integral-transforms/hartley-transform] That is, the real and imaginary parts of the Fourier transform are simply given by the even and odd parts of the Hartley transform, respectively.
[src:integral-transforms/hartley-transform] where $\ {\mathcal {R_{e}}}\$ and $\ {\mathcal {I_{m}}}\$ denote the real and imaginary parts.
[src:integral-transforms/hartley-transform] The Hartley transform is a real linear operator, and is symmetric (and Hermitian).
[src:integral-transforms/hartley-transform] From the symmetric and self-inverse properties, it follows that the transform is a unitary operator (indeed, orthogonal).
[src:integral-transforms/hartley-transform] Similar to the Fourier transform, the Hartley transform of an even/odd function is even/odd, respectively.
[src:integral-transforms/hartley-transform] The properties of the *Hartley kernel*, for which Hartley introduced the name *cas* for the function (from *cosine and sine*) in 1942, follow directly from trigonometry, and its definition as a phase-shifted trigonometric function $\operatorname {cas} (t)={\sqrt {2}}\sin(t+\pi /4)=\sin(t)+\cos(t)$ .
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] In mathematics and signal processing, the **Hilbert transform** is a specific singular integral that takes a function, *u*(*t*) of a real variable and produces another function of a real variable H(*u*)(*t*).
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] The Hilbert transform is given by the Cauchy principal value of the convolution with the function $1/(\pi t)$ (see § Definition).
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] The Hilbert transform has a particularly simple representation in the frequency domain: It imparts a phase shift of ±90° (π/2 radians) to every frequency component of a function, the sign of the shift depending on the sign of the frequency (see § Relationship with the Fourier transform).
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] The Hilbert transform is important in signal processing, where it is a component of the analytic representation of a real-valued signal *u*(*t*).
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] The Hilbert transform was first introduced by David Hilbert in this setting, to solve a special case of the Riemann–Hilbert problem for analytic functions.
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] The Hilbert transform of u can be thought of as the convolution of *u*(*t*) with the function *h*(*t*) = ⁠1/π*t*⁠, known as the Cauchy kernel.
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] Because 1/t is not integrable across *t* = 0, the integral defining the convolution does not always converge.
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] Instead, the Hilbert transform is defined using the Cauchy principal value (denoted here by p.v.).
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] provided this integral exists as a principal value.
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] This is precisely the convolution of u with the tempered distribution p.v. ⁠1/π*t*⁠.
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] provided the integrals defining both iterations converge in a suitable sense.
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] In particular, the inverse transform is $-\operatorname {H}$ .
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] This fact can most easily be seen by considering the effect of the Hilbert transform on the Fourier transform of *u*(*t*) (see § Relationship with the Fourier transform below).
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] For an analytic function in the upper half-plane, the Hilbert transform describes the relationship between the real part and the imaginary part of the boundary values.
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] That is, if *f*(*z*) is analytic in the upper half complex plane {*z* : Im{*z*} > 0}, and *u*(*t*) = Re{*f* (*t* + 0·*i*)}, then Im{*f*(*t* + 0·*i*)} = H(*u*)(*t*) up to an additive constant, provided this Hilbert transform exists.
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] In signal processing the Hilbert transform of *u*(*t*) is commonly denoted by ${\hat {u}}(t)$ .
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] However, in mathematics, this notation is already extensively used to denote the Fourier transform of *u*(*t*).
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] Occasionally, the Hilbert transform may be denoted by ${\tilde {u}}(t)$ .
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] Furthermore, many sources define the Hilbert transform as the negative of the one defined here.
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] The Hilbert transform arose in Hilbert's 1905 work on a problem Riemann posed concerning analytic functions, which has come to be known as the Riemann–Hilbert problem.
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] Hilbert's work was mainly concerned with the Hilbert transform for functions defined on the circle.
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] Some of his earlier work related to the Discrete Hilbert Transform dates back to lectures he gave in Göttingen.
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] The results were later published by Hermann Weyl in his dissertation.
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] Schur improved Hilbert's results about the discrete Hilbert transform and extended them to the integral case.
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] These results were restricted to the spaces *L*2 and ℓ2.
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] The Hilbert transform was a motivating example for Antoni Zygmund and Alberto Calderón during their study of singular integrals.
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] Their investigations have played a fundamental role in modern harmonic analysis.
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] Various generalizations of the Hilbert transform, such as the bilinear and trilinear Hilbert transforms are still active areas of research today.
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] The Hilbert transform is a multiplier operator.
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] The multiplier of H is *σ*H(*ω*) = −*i* sgn(*ω*), where sgn is the signum function.
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] where ${\mathcal {F}}$ denotes the Fourier transform.
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] Since sgn(*x*) = sgn(2π*x*), it follows that this result applies to the three common definitions of ${\mathcal {F}}$ .
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] When the Hilbert transform is applied twice, the phase of the negative and positive frequency components of *u*(*t*) are respectively shifted by +180° and −180°, which are equivalent amounts.
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] In the following table, the frequency parameter $\omega$ is real.
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] The Hilbert transform of the sin and cos functions can be defined by taking the principal value of the integral at infinity.
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] This definition agrees with the result of defining the Hilbert transform distributionally.
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] An extensive table of Hilbert transforms is available.
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] Note that the Hilbert transform of a constant is zero.
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] It is by no means obvious that the Hilbert transform is well-defined at all, as the improper integral defining it must converge in a suitable sense.
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] However, the Hilbert transform is well-defined for a broad class of functions, namely those in $L^{p}(\mathbb {R} )$ for 1 < *p* < ∞.
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] The limit function is also in $L^{p}(\mathbb {R} )$ and is in fact the limit in the mean of the improper integral as well.
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] as *ε* → 0 in the Lp norm, as well as pointwise almost everywhere, by the Titchmarsh theorem.
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] In the case *p* = 1, the Hilbert transform still converges pointwise almost everywhere, but may itself fail to be integrable, even locally.
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] In particular, convergence in the mean does not in general happen in this case.
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] The Hilbert transform of an *L*1 function does converge, however, in *L*1-weak, and the Hilbert transform is a bounded operator from *L*1 to *L*1,w.
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] An easy way to find the best $C_{p}$ for p being a power of 2 is through the so-called Cotlar's identity that $(\operatorname {H} f)^{2}=f^{2}+2\operatorname {H} (f\operatorname {H} f)$ for all real valued f.
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] The same best constants hold for the periodic Hilbert transform.
