[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] The number theoretic Hilbert transform is an extension of the discrete Hilbert transform to integers modulo an appropriate prime number.
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] In this it follows the generalization of discrete Fourier transform to number theoretic transforms.
[src:integral-transforms/hilbert-transform] The number theoretic Hilbert transform can be used to generate sets of orthogonal discrete sequences.
[src:integral-transforms/integral-transform] The transformed function can generally be mapped back to the original function space using the *inverse transform*.
[src:integral-transforms/integral-transform] The input of this transform is a function *f*, and the output is another function *$Tf$*.
[src:integral-transforms/integral-transform] An integral transform is a particular kind of mathematical operator.
[src:integral-transforms/integral-transform] There are numerous useful integral transforms.
[src:integral-transforms/integral-transform] Each is specified by a choice of the function K of two variables, that is called the **kernel** or **nucleus** of the transform.
[src:integral-transforms/integral-transform] A *symmetric kernel* is one that is unchanged when the two variables are permuted; it is a kernel function *K* such that $K(t,u)=K(u,t)$ .
[src:integral-transforms/integral-transform] In the theory of integral equations, symmetric kernels correspond to self-adjoint operators.
[src:integral-transforms/integral-transform] There are many classes of problems that are difficult to solve—or at least quite unwieldy algebraically—in their original representations.
[src:integral-transforms/integral-transform] An integral transform "maps" an equation from its original "domain" into another domain, in which manipulating and solving the equation may be much easier than in the original domain.
[src:integral-transforms/integral-transform] The solution can then be mapped back to the original domain with the inverse of the integral transform.
[src:integral-transforms/integral-transform] There are many applications of probability that rely on integral transforms, such as "pricing kernel" or stochastic discount factor, or the smoothing of data recovered from robust statistics; see kernel (statistics).
[src:integral-transforms/integral-transform] The precursor of the transforms were the Fourier series to express functions in finite intervals.
[src:integral-transforms/integral-transform] Later the Fourier transform was developed to remove the requirement of finite intervals.
[src:integral-transforms/integral-transform] The sines and cosines in the Fourier series are an example of an orthonormal basis.
[src:integral-transforms/integral-transform] As an example of an application of integral transforms, consider the Laplace transform.
[src:integral-transforms/integral-transform] This is a technique that maps differential or integro-differential equations in the "time" domain into polynomial equations in what is termed the "complex frequency" domain.
[src:integral-transforms/integral-transform] (Complex frequency is similar to actual, physical frequency but rather more general.
[src:integral-transforms/integral-transform] Employing the inverse transform, *i.e.*, the inverse procedure of the original Laplace transform, one obtains a time-domain solution.
[src:integral-transforms/integral-transform] In this example, polynomials in the complex frequency domain (typically occurring in the denominator) correspond to power series in the time domain, while axial shifts in the complex frequency domain correspond to damping by decaying exponentials in the time domain.
[src:integral-transforms/integral-transform] Other integral transforms find special applicability within other scientific and mathematical disciplines.
[src:integral-transforms/integral-transform] This states that the total amplitude $\psi (x,t)$ to arrive at $(x,t)$ is the sum (the integral) over all possible values $x'$ of the total amplitude $\psi (x',t')$ to arrive at the point $(x',t')$ multiplied by the amplitude to go from $x'$ to x [i.e. $K(x,t;x',t')$ ].
[src:integral-transforms/integral-transform] It is often referred to as the propagator for a given system.
[src:integral-transforms/integral-transform] This (physics) kernel is the kernel of the integral transform.
[src:integral-transforms/integral-transform] However, for each quantum system, there is a different kernel.
[src:integral-transforms/integral-transform] In the limits of integration for the inverse transform, *c* is a constant which depends on the nature of the transform function.
[src:integral-transforms/integral-transform] For example, for the one and two-sided Laplace transform, *c* must be greater than the largest real part of the zeroes of the transform function.
[src:integral-transforms/integral-transform] Note that there are alternative notations and conventions for the Fourier transform.
[src:integral-transforms/integral-transform] Here integral transforms are defined for functions on the real numbers, but they can be defined more generally for functions on a group.
[src:integral-transforms/integral-transform] Although the properties of integral transforms vary widely, they have some properties in common.
[src:integral-transforms/integral-transform] For example, every integral transform is a linear operator, since the integral is a linear operator, and in fact if the kernel is allowed to be a generalized function then all linear operators are integral transforms (a properly formulated version of this statement is the Schwartz kernel theorem).
[src:integral-transforms/integral-transform] The general theory of such integral equations is known as Fredholm theory.
[src:integral-transforms/integral-transform] In this theory, the kernel is understood to be a compact operator acting on a Banach space of functions.
[src:integral-transforms/integral-transform] Depending on the situation, the kernel is then variously referred to as the Fredholm operator, the nuclear operator or the Fredholm kernel.
[src:integral-transforms/stieltjes-transformation] Under certain conditions we can reconstitute the density function *ρ* starting from its Stieltjes transformation thanks to the inverse formula of Stieltjes–Perron.
[src:integral-transforms/stieltjes-transformation] Integrating any function $\rho (t)$ against *that* would pick out the value $\rho (t_{0})$ .
[src:integral-transforms/stieltjes-transformation] Rather integrating $\int _{-\infty }^{\infty }{\frac {\varepsilon /\pi }{(t-t_{0})^{2}+\varepsilon ^{2}}}\rho (t)\,dt$ for some $\varepsilon >0$ instead produces the value at $t_{0}$ for some smoothed variant of $\rho$ —the smaller the value of $\varepsilon$ , the less smoothing is applied.
[src:integral-transforms/stieltjes-transformation] Used in this way, the factor ${\frac {\varepsilon /\pi }{(t-t_{0})^{2}+\varepsilon ^{2}}}$ is also known as the Poisson kernel (for the half-plane).
[src:integral-transforms/stieltjes-transformation] If instead the measure has a point mass at x , then the limit as $\varepsilon \to 0^{+}$ of the integral diverges, and the Stieltjes transform $S_{\mu }$ has a pole at x .
[src:integral-transforms/stieltjes-transformation] The correspondence ${\textstyle (f,g)\mapsto \int _{I}f(t)g(t)\rho (t)\,dt}$ defines an inner product on the space of continuous functions on the interval I.
[src:integral-transforms/stieltjes-transformation] Since these two sequences of polynomials satisfy the same recurrence relation in three terms, we can develop a continued fraction for the Stieltjes transformation whose successive convergents are the fractions *Fn*(*z*).
[src:integral-transforms/stieltjes-transformation] The Stieltjes transformation can also be used to construct from the density *ρ* an effective measure for transforming the secondary polynomials into an orthogonal system.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] In mathematics, a **wavelet series** is a representation of a square-integrable (real- or complex-valued) function by a certain orthonormal series generated by a wavelet.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] This article provides a formal, mathematical definition of an **orthonormal wavelet** and of the **integral wavelet transform**.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] A function $\psi \,\in \,L^{2}(\mathbb {R} )$ is called an **orthonormal wavelet** if it can be used to define a Hilbert basis, that is, a complete orthonormal system for the Hilbert space of square-integrable functions on the real line.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] The Hilbert basis is constructed as the family of functions $\{\psi _{jk}:\,j,\,k\,\in \,\mathbb {Z} \}$ by means of dyadic translations and dilations of $\psi \,$ , $\psi _{jk}(x)=2^{\frac {j}{2}}\psi \left(2^{j}x-k\right),$ for integers $j,\,k\,\in \,\mathbb {Z}$ .
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] with convergence of the series understood to be convergence in norm.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] Such a representation of f is known as a **wavelet series**.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] This implies that an orthonormal wavelet is self-dual.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] Here, $a=2^{-j}$ is called the **binary dilation** or **dyadic dilation**, and $b=k2^{-j}$ is the **binary** or **dyadic position**.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] The fundamental idea of wavelet transforms is that the transformation should allow only changes in time extension, but not shape, imposing a restriction on choosing suitable basis functions.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] Changes in the time extension are expected to conform to the corresponding analysis frequency of the basis function.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] where t represents time and $\omega$ angular frequency ( $\omega =2\pi f$ , where f is ordinary frequency).
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] The higher the required resolution in time, the lower the resolution in frequency has to be.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] The larger the extension of the analysis windows is chosen, the larger is the value of $\Delta t$ .
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] In other words, the basis function $\psi$ can be regarded as an impulse response of a system with which the function $x(t)$ has been filtered.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] The transformed signal provides information about the time and the frequency.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] Therefore, wavelet-transformation contains information similar to the short-time-Fourier-transformation, but with additional special properties of the wavelets, which show up at the resolution in time at higher analysis frequencies of the basis function.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] The difference in time resolution at ascending frequencies for the Fourier transform and the wavelet transform is shown below.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] Note however, that the frequency resolution is decreasing for increasing frequencies while the temporal resolution increases.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] This consequence of the Fourier uncertainty principle is not correctly displayed in the Figure.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] This shows that wavelet transformation is good in time resolution of high frequencies, while for slowly varying functions, the frequency resolution is remarkable.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] Another example: The analysis of three superposed sinusoidal signals $y(t)\;=\;\sin(2\pi f_{0}t)\;+\;\sin(4\pi f_{0}t)\;+\;\sin(8\pi f_{0}t)$ with STFT and wavelet-transformation.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] This produces as many coefficients as there are pixels in the image (i.e., there is no compression yet since it is only a transform).
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] These coefficients can then be compressed more easily because the information is statistically concentrated in just a few coefficients.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] This principle is called transform coding.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] After that, the coefficients are quantized and the quantized values are entropy encoded and/or run length encoded.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] A few 1D and 2D applications of wavelet compression use a technique called "wavelet footprints".
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] For most natural images, the spectrum density of lower frequency is higher.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] As a result, information of the low frequency signal (reference signal) is generally preserved, while the information in the detail signal is discarded.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] Wavelet image compression system involves filters and decimation, so it can be described as a linear shift-variant system.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] The transformation system contains two analysis filters (a low pass filter $h_{0}(n)$ and a high pass filter $h_{1}(n)$ ), a decimation process, an interpolation process, and two synthesis filters ( $g_{0}(n)$ and $g_{1}(n)$ ).
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] The compression and reconstruction system generally involves low frequency components, which is the analysis filters $h_{0}(n)$ for image compression and the synthesis filters $g_{0}(n)$ for reconstruction.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] To evaluate such system, we can input an impulse $\delta (n-n_{i})$ and observe its reconstruction $h(n-n_{i})$ ; The optimal wavelet are those who bring minimum shift variance and sidelobe to $h(n-n_{i})$ .
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] Even though wavelet with strict shift variance is not realistic, it is possible to select wavelet with only slight shift variance.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] By observing the impulse responses of the two filters, we can conclude that the second filter is less sensitive to the input location (i.e. it is less shift variant).
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] Another important issue for image compression and reconstruction is the system's oscillatory behavior, which might lead to severe undesired artifacts in the reconstructed image.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] To achieve this, the wavelet filters should have a large peak to sidelobe ratio.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] So far we have discussed about one-dimension transformation of the image compression system.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] This issue can be extended to two dimension, while a more general term - shiftable multiscale transforms - is proposed.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] As mentioned earlier, impulse response can be used to evaluate the image compression/reconstruction system.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] For the input sequence $x(n)=\delta (n-n_{i})$ , the reference signal $r_{1}(n)$ after one level of decomposition is $x(n)*h_{0}(n)$ goes through decimation by a factor of two, while $h_{0}(n)$ is a low pass filter.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] Similarly, the next reference signal $r_{2}(n)$ is obtained by $r_{1}(n)*h_{0}(n)$ goes through decimation by a factor of two.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] After L levels of decomposition (and decimation), the analysis response is obtained by retaining one out of every $2^{L}$ samples: $h_{A}^{(L)}(n,n_{i})=f_{h0}^{(L)}(n-n_{i}/2^{L})$ .
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] On the other hand, to reconstruct the signal x(n), we can consider a reference signal $r_{L}(n)=\delta (n-n_{j})$ .
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] If the detail signals $d_{i}(n)$ are equal to zero for $1\leq i\leq L$ , then the reference signal at the previous stage ( $L-1$ stage) is $r_{L-1}(n)=g_{0}(n-2n_{j})$ , which is obtained by interpolating $r_{L}(n)$ and convoluting with $g_{0}(n)$ .
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] Similarly, the procedure is iterated to obtain the reference signal $r(n)$ at stage $L-2,L-3,....,1$ .
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] After L iterations, the synthesis impulse response is calculated: $h_{s}^{(L)}(n,n_{i})=f_{g0}^{(L)}(n/2^{L}-n_{j})$ , which relates the reference signal $r_{L}(n)$ and the reconstructed signal.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] Finally, the peak to first sidelobe ratio and the average second sidelobe of the overall impulse response $h_{AS}^{(L)}(n,n_{i})$ can be used to evaluate the wavelet image compression performance.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] Using a wavelet transform, the wavelet compression methods are adequate for representing transients, such as percussion sounds in audio, or high-frequency components in two-dimensional images, for example an image of stars on a night sky.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] This means that the transient elements of a data signal can be represented by a smaller amount of information than would be the case if some other transform, such as the more widespread discrete cosine transform, had been used.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] While wavelet transforms offer theoretical advantages, their practical limitations have effectively limited wavelet compression to analyzing localized changes and transient signals.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] Despite decades of research, wavelet-based compression systems for common multimedia like audio and video do not consistently match the efficiency and perceptual quality of current Discrete Cosine Transform-based systems.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] For one-dimensional data like audio or ECGs, wavelets excel at representing and compressing transient signals—sudden, isolated events such as a drum hit in music or the sharp peaks in a heart rhythm.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] For example, the discrete wavelet transform has been successfully applied for the compression of electrocardiograph (ECG) signals.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] However, for smooth, periodic signals, which make up much of typical audio, harmonic analysis in the frequency domain with Fourier-related transforms achieve better compression and sound quality.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] Compressing data that has both transient and periodic characteristics may be done with hybrid techniques that use wavelets along with traditional harmonic analysis.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] For example, the Vorbis audio codec primarily uses the modified discrete cosine transform to compress audio (which is generally smooth and periodic), however allows the addition of a hybrid wavelet filter bank for improved reproduction of transients.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] For higher-dimensional data, wavelet compression faces significant challenges.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] In video, for instance, modern compression techniques such as intra coding and motion compensation (predicting parts of an image based on what's next to it spatially and temporally) and mixed and dynamic block sizes become incredibly complex with wavelets because of their overlapping nature.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] This complexity translates to more processing power and slower speed, making them less practical for widespread use.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] Furthermore, while wavelets might score well on traditional measures such as PSNR, DCT blocks create a perception of sharpness that wavelets often lack, requiring higher bitrates to achieve similar subjective quality.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] Wavelets have some slight benefits over Fourier transforms in reducing computations when examining specific frequencies.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] However, they are rarely more sensitive, and indeed, the common Morlet wavelet is mathematically identical to a short-time Fourier transform using a Gaussian window function.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] The exception is when searching for signals of a known, non-sinusoidal shape (e.g., heartbeats); in that case, using matched wavelets can outperform standard STFT/Morlet analyses.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] The wavelet transform can provide us with the frequency of the signals and the time associated to those frequencies, making it very convenient for its application in numerous fields.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] For instance, signal processing of accelerations for gait analysis, for fault detection, for the analysis of seasonal displacements of landslides, for design of low power pacemakers and also in ultra-wideband (UWB) wireless communications.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] A convolution can be implemented as a multiplication in the frequency domain.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] With this the following approach of implementation results into: There are many different types of wavelet transforms for specific purposes.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] See also a full list of wavelet-related transforms but the common ones are listed below: Mexican hat wavelet, Haar Wavelet, Daubechies wavelet, triangular wavelet.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] Fault detection in electrical power systems.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] Locally adaptive statistical estimation of functions whose smoothness varies substantially over the domain, or more specifically, estimation of functions that are sparse in the wavelet domain.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] For processing temporal signals in real time, it is essential that the wavelet filters do not access signal values from the future as well as that minimal temporal latencies can be obtained.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] Time-causal wavelets representations have been developed by Szu et al and Lindeberg, with the latter method also involving a memory-efficient time-recursive implementation.
[src:integral-transforms/wavelet-transform] Synchro-squeezed transform can significantly enhance temporal and frequency resolution of time-frequency representation obtained using conventional wavelet transform.
